## Migration: Thread.Abort → Cooperative Cancellation (.NET 8)

### Why This Breaks

In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — there is no way to forcibly terminate a managed thread. You must switch to **cooperative cancellation** using `CancellationToken`.

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking can be interrupted
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — just continue to exit the loop naturally
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Wait for the thread to finish gracefully
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

        // If thread is still alive after timeout, you cannot force-kill it.
        // Log a warning — see pitfalls below.
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

---

### Key Changes

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) |
|---|---|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationToken.IsCancellationRequested` |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Not needed — loop continues or exits naturally |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` before abort | `Thread.Join(timeout)` after cancel |

---

### Critical: Make Blocking Calls Cancellable

The original `GetNextItem()` "may block" — **this is the hardest part**. Cancellation only works if the blocked code cooperates. Examples:

```csharp
// If using a BlockingCollection<T>:
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException on cancel
}

// If using a polling wait:
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    while (!_queue.TryDequeue(out var item))
    {
        token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(100); // wakes on cancel or timeout
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    }
    return item;
}
```

---

### Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Solution |
|---|---|
| `GetNextItem()` blocks forever, ignoring the token | Pass `CancellationToken` to all blocking calls. Replace `Thread.Sleep(ms)` with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)`. |
| Expecting immediate stop after `Cancel()` | Cooperative cancellation only fires at the next checkpoint. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` between expensive operations. |
| Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource` | It's `IDisposable` — leaking it leaks timers/callbacks. Implement `IDisposable` on your class. |
| Truly uncooperative code (e.g., native call that blocks indefinitely) | Move to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()`. There is no in-process equivalent of `Thread.Abort` in modern .NET. |
| Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly | Use `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` filter to avoid catching unrelated OCEs from other tokens. |

---

### If You Absolutely Need Force-Kill Semantics

There is **no in-process replacement**. Your options:

1. **Redesign** — make all work cancellation-aware (preferred)
2. **Separate process** — `Process.Start()` + `Process.Kill()` for uncooperative work
3. **Accept the risk** — abandon the thread (it leaks but the process continues)
